{code}

The check by default does a nested group check, which does not support DN user membership restrictions, loading all members of the group (isNestedMember(...)).

{code}
    protected boolean isGroupMember(String group, String principal, boolean directMemberOnly)
    {
        try
        {
            if (directMemberOnly)
            {
                Name groupDN = getGroupDN(group);
                Name principalDN = getPrincipalDN(principal);
                return isDirectMember(ldapPropertiesMapper.getGroupFilter(), groupDN, ldapPropertiesMapper.getGroupMemberAttribute(), principalDN);
            }
            else
            {
                return isNestedMember(group, principal);
            }
{code}

Within the {{isDirectMember}} and {{isNestedMember}} the {{groupDN - buildDN(..)}} lookup method can also be enhanced to not pull back the memberOf attributes when building the DN. These attributes by default will be pulled into Crowd which can otherwise be ignored.

When creating a 'generic ldap' connector, the default values for the group object type are not consistent.

In the JSP, default values being populated from the LDAP properties mapper are not identical and both should be {{groupOfUniqueNames}}

{code}
form.groupObjectClass.value = 'groupOfUniqueNames';
form.groupObjectFilter.value = '(objectclass=posixGroup)';
{code}

We are using email addresses as the username - when the email address contains a plus character (+), we are unable to create this user against an Open LDAP directory:

Eg: a username of bob+builder@gmail.com will return the following error:

{quote}
Invalid name: cn=bob+builder@gmail.com,ou=people,ou=customer,dc=atlassian,dc=com; nested exception is javax.naming.InvalidNameException: Invalid name: cn=bob+builder@gmail.com,ou=people,ou=customer,dc=atlassian,dc=com; remaining name 'cn=bob+builder@gmail.com,ou=people,ou=customer,dc=atlassian,dc=com'
{quote}
